                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d584">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.612 Grapes–Spain/200a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-04-20T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 20, 1934—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>25. As a result of experiments carried on over a considerable period of time by
                    the Bureau of Entomology the Department of Agriculture <pb facs="0795" n="695"
                        xml:id="pg_695"/> announced last night that it had decided to permit,
                    effective May 1, 1934, grapes of the Vinifera type from regions in which the
                    Mediterranean fruit fly occurs to be entered at the port of New York and such
                    other northern ports as may subsequently be designated provided the grapes are
                    packed in tight barrels or other approved containers so constructed as to
                    prevent the escape, pending sterilization, of any stages of the Mediterranean
                    fruit fly and are delivered within 24 hours from the time of unloading to an
                    approved sterilization plant at which the grapes will be subjected to cooling
                    until the approximate center of the fruit in the package reaches a temperature
                    of 30°–31° Fahrenheit and will then be held at that temperature for 15 days. The
                    Spanish Embassy here has been informed as to details by the Department of
                    Agriculture. You may inform the Foreign Office of the foregoing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
